Because DF and UFL is an awkward buffer combination for parity, I solve parity like so:

1. Memorise corners first. If there is an odd number of targets, you have parity.
2. Memorise edges, with UF and UL swapped. This approach has a few advantages:
- You can float UF and UL to UB and UL with a U move and solve most parity cases with like OP with a Y-perm = fast.
- For some of the more awkward cases, you can instead set-up to Jb-perm.
- A lot of these algs have cancellations.
- You can also use ZBLL algs for some really fast cases.
3. Solve edges first, which will feel like solving an even number of targets (easier for memo.)
4. Solve corners last.

failures.text: Because DF and UFL is an awkward buffer combination for parity, I solve parity like so:

failures.failure_description: Contains characters that don't correspond to anything in cubing notation.
